data.content:
Yes — MSTest v3.3+ supports **typed data sources** via `TestDataRow<T>` and generic overloads, eliminating the `object[]` boxing:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[TestData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Key changes:**
- Replace `[DynamicData]` with `[TestData]` (the modern unified attribute).
- Return `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>` (tuples) instead of `IEnumerable<object[]>`.
- This gives you **compile-time type checking** — a mismatched type in the data will fail at build time, not at runtime.

> Requires **MSTest 3.3+** (`Microsoft.Testing.Framework`). If you're still on MSTest v2, `DynamicData` with `object[]` remains your only built-in option.
